    "timeout_seconds":{"type":"integer"},"marshal_expected_wave":{"type":"object",
    "properties":{"wave_target":{"type":"string"},"wave_mode":{"type":"string"},
    "source_range":{"type":"string"},"anchor_index_begin":{"type":"string"},
    "anchor_index_end":{"type":"string"},"model_state_inputs":{"type":"object"}}}},
    "additionalProperties":false})"},
```

## Proposed Review Outcome

Please recommend one of these directions, or a better one:

### Option A: Add Target-First Operator Packet Only

Add `hero.marshal.prepare_target_dispatch`. It combines target lookup, advice
validation, Runtime policy/wave inspection, and blocker grouping. It does not
resolve symbolic checkpoint hints except to report them.

Pros:

```text
- smallest change
- does not touch Lattice semantics
- immediately simplifies operator view
```

Cons:

```text
- still leaves checkpoint resolution manual
- may not be enough to make target pursuit feel one-step
```

### Option B: Add Read-Only Symbolic Plan-Input Resolution

Add a read-only resolution step for `latest_satisfying:<target_id>` values.
Either Lattice plan_target materializes them when requested, or Marshal calls a
Lattice selector/closure query to resolve them.

Pros:

```text
- closes the biggest operational gap
- makes "target -> dry-run readiness" much smoother
- still read-only and proof-preserving
```

Cons:

```text
- needs careful ownership: latest_satisfying belongs to Lattice, not Marshal
- must not become best-model selection or performance ranking
```

### Option C: Add Wave Alignment Preview

When Runtime active wave does not match the advised wave, return a proposed
`kikijyeba.settings.wave.dsl` patch or overlay text, but do not apply it.

Pros:

```text
- makes active-wave mismatch actionable
- keeps Config/Runtime mutation out of Marshal
```

Cons:

```text
- risks looking like Marshal owns config editing
- may be better as Config Hero or Runtime Hero preview responsibility
```

### My Preferred Packet

I would implement A plus the read-only half of B:

```text
hero.marshal.prepare_target_dispatch
  - target-first
  - no execution by default
  - calls Lattice plan_target
  - tries to resolve latest_satisfying through Lattice-owned read-only logic
  - validates advice/request
  - reads Runtime policy/wave
  - reports operator blocker bucket
  - emits exact next action
```

If checkpoint resolution is not available, it should still return a clear
operator packet:

```text
blocked: unresolved_model_state
resolve:
  PLAN_INPUT_MDN_CHECKPOINT from channel_mdn_train_core_no_test_leakage
  PLAN_INPUT_REPRESENTATION_CHECKPOINT from vicreg_train_core_ready
runtime_wave:
  already aligned on target/mode/range
next_action:
  ask Lattice for concrete latest_satisfying checkpoint paths, then dry-run
```

The final design should keep this invariant:

```text
Marshal simplifies the operation, not the proof.
```
